Judgment has been reserved in the SIU's joinder application. Aviwe Mtila has more. #eNCA Courtesy #DStv403  JOHANNESBURG - The Special Investigating Unit (SIU) has repeated that proceeds of the Digital Vibes tender went to the Mkhize family. Advocate Barry Roux represented the investigating unit at the Special Tribunal on Tuesday. READ: COVID-19 Corruption | SIU, Digital Vibes to go before tribunal Its submission claims that R1.8m was paid towards the bond of May Mkhize, wife of the former Health Minister. Judgment in this matter has been reserved.    The SIU also implicated Tusokuhle Farming which is owned by Mkhize's son Dedani. But its legal representative says there’s no evidence that they received any of the tainted money. Advocate Gregory Harpur argued that there is no link between Digital vibes and his client’s farm. Watch the proceedings in the recording below. The Special Tribunal is hearing what is called a joinder application in the matter.